ologists demonstrates why the burgeoning field of conservation biology must continue to rely on the insights of population genetics if we are to preserve the diversity of living species. Technological and theoretical developments throughout the 1990s have allowed for important new insights into how populations have evolved in response to past selection pressures, while providing a broad new understanding of the genetic structure of natural populations. The authors explore these advances and argue for the applicability of new genetic methods in conservation biology. The volume covers such topics as the reasons for extinctions, the best ways to measure biodiversity, and the benefits and drawbacks of policies like captive breeding. Genetics and the Extinction of Species is a rich source of information for biologists and policymakers who want to learn more about the host of tools, theories, and approaches available for conserving biodiversity. In addition to the editors, the contributors to the volume are William Amos, Rebecca Cann, Kathryn Rodriguez-Clark, Leslie Douglas, Leonard Freed, Paul Harvey, Kent Holsinger, Russell Lande, and Helen Steers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aConservation biology. 0aGenetica de poblacions. 0aNaturaxProtecció. 0aPopulation genetics. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Evolution.2bisacsh  aEgyptian mummy.  aEuropean badger.  aMartian meteorite.  aNeandertal.  aadaptive radiation.  aakiapolaau.  aallelic diversity.  aancient DNA.  aassimilation.  abalancing selection.  acaptive breeding.  acarrying capacity.  acichlid fish.  acockroaches.  acontamination.  acrested honeycreeper.  adamaged DNA.  adeclining-population paradigm.  adinosaur.  aecomorph.  aeconomic factors.  aenvironmental policy.  aexotic species.  aextreme environments.  af